               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17730113-29-person323">
                  Edward
                   Dalton
               <interp inst="t17730113-29-person323" type="surname" value="Dalton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17730113-29-person323" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17730113-29-person323" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I <rs id="t17730113-29-viclabel171" type="occupation">keep a chandler's shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17730113-29-victim322 t17730113-29-viclabel171"></join>. Upon the 13th of December last, about nine at night, I heard the bell of my shop door; I went into the shop and missed this sugar; I followed the prisoner, seized him, and charged him with the fact; he denied it; I brought him into the house and then he confessed it, and said if I would go over the way with him, he would let me know where the sugar was; he had been three times at my house, and had changed his dress, which made me suspect him.</p>
               <p>- Lyons. I am a constable; I took the prisoner to a public house; there he confessed he had taken the sugar and would shew us where it was.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17730113-29-person324">
                  Hannah
                   Dalton
               <interp inst="t17730113-29-person324" type="surname" value="Dalton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17730113-29-person324" type="given" value="Hannah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17730113-29-person324" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner came to our house three times; first in a striped jacket; then he changed his dress; the third time there was an alarm by the bell; he was followed and brought in by my husband, and he confessed he took it; the confession was first made in the house.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I know nothing of it; I did not know what I did when I confessed; they threatened to put me into irons.</p>
